{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 18:28:06.371799", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary of observed behavior\\n- Overall control-plane health: All EBGP sessions between leaves, spines, and the super-spine are established and stable. The fabric is exchanging routes as expected.\\n- Data-plane anomaly: Traffic to subnet 10.0.1.0/24 (host pc_0_1: 10.0.1.2) is being steered to a more-specific blackhole route 10.0.1.0/30, causing loss of reachability to 10.0.1.1–10.0.1.2 across the fabric.\\n\\nKey evidence\\n1) Host configs\\n- pc_0_0: 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1\\n- pc_0_1: 10.0.1.2/24, default via 10.0.1.1\\nThese are correct for the stated topology.\\n\\n2) Reachability tests\\n- Fabric-wide reachability tests included many successful inter-host pings, but targeted pings involving 10.0.1.2 timed out when executed (tool returned TIMEOUT). This aligns with a routing blackhole specifically affecting 10.0.1.0/30.\\n\\n3) Routing on leaf_router_0_1 (the leaf for 10.0.1.0/24)\\n- Running config includes:\\n  - ip route 10.0.1.0/30 Null0\\n  - address-family ipv4 unicast: network 10.0.1.0/24 and network 10.0.1.0/30\\n- Forwarding table:\\n  - C>* 10.0.1.0/24 is directly connected, eth4\\n  - S>* 10.0.1.0/30 [1/0] unreachable (blackhole)\\n- Specific lookup:\\n  - show ip route 10.0.1.2 → “Routing entry for 10.0.1.0/30 … unreachable (blackhole)”\\n\\nImplication: On this leaf, the static blackhole /30 is a longer prefix than the connected /24 and thus wins, dropping traffic destined to 10.0.1.1–10.0.1.2 locally.\\n\\n4) Propagation of the blackhole route\\n- The /30 is also advertised via BGP by leaf_router_0_1 and is selected across the fabric:\\n  - leaf_router_0_0: B>* 10.0.1.0/30 via 172.16.0.32; B>* 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.48 (the /30 is more specific and preferred for 10.0.1.1–10.0.1.2)\\n  - spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1: B>* 10.0.1.0/30 present and preferred\\n  - super_spine_router_0: B>* 10.0.1.0/30 present and preferred\\n- BGP tables confirm advertisement of both 10.0.1.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/30, with the /30 considered best by longest-match in forwarding.\\n\\n5) BGP session health\\n- leaf_router_0_0: 4 neighbors, PfxRcd 8 each\\n- leaf_router_0_1: 4 neighbors, PfxRcd 7 each (minor count difference; not material to the issue)\\n- spines and super-spine: all neighbors established; both 10.0.1.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/30 are present in the BGP RIBs and the /30 is installed in the FIB\\n\\nFault localization\\n- Faulty device: leaf_router_0_1 (the leaf serving 10.0.1.0/24).\\n- Why: It contains a static blackhole route for 10.0.1.0/30 and intentionally advertises this prefix via BGP. This results in:\\n  - Local blackhole of traffic to 10.0.1.1–10.0.1.2 on the leaf itself.\\n  - Network-wide preference for the more-specific 10.0.1.0/30 over 10.0.1.0/24, steering all traffic for 10.0.1.1–10.0.1.2 to that leaf where it is dropped.\\n\\nRoot cause\\n- Misconfiguration on leaf_router_0_1:\\n  - Static route: ip route 10.0.1.0/30 Null0 creates a blackhole.\\n  - BGP configuration advertises 10.0.1.0/30, propagating the blackhole across the Clos fabric.\\n- Because longest prefix match is used, 10.0.1.0/30 overrides the intended 10.0.1.0/24 host network, effectively isolating host pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2) from the rest of the network.\\n\\nImpact assessment\\n- Any traffic destined to 10.0.1.1–10.0.1.2 is routed to leaf_router_0_1 and dropped. This breaks connectivity to pc_0_1 and likely prevents remote management pings to 10.0.1.1.\\n- Other subnets appear unaffected; BGP adjacencies are stable and other routes function normally.\\n\\nNo remediation is proposed here per instructions., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='8e26c7c2-8bfc-4dbf-b789-b71a9d07b1a6'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
